None of the patients had evidence of HIV infection, nor were treated with steroids or anti-TB drugs at the time of first sampling. Reactivity to this epitope was completely abrogated in the CD8+ depleted cultures, indicating this epitope is CD8+ restricted.The lymph node mononuclear cells used in the assay were from a single cat that was found to have broad reactivity to the individual peptides selected for the gene-specific pools. The patients with BD were grouped as having active disease (6 patients) or inactive disease (8 patients) at the time of blood examination. Active disease was defined as the presence of characteristic BD symptoms, including severe oral/genital ulcers and ocular involvement. All 6 patients with active disease were not receiving corticosteroids or immunosuppressants at the time of the blood examination. The epitope specific T cell line was generated by repetitively stimulating peripheral blood T cells from BD patients with the epitope in vitro. The group included 8 HLA-B51-positive and 6 HLA-B51-negative patients. Cytotoxicity was measured using a lactate dehydrogenase release ELISA.  Whole PBMC were stimulated with peptide for 10 to 14 days in the presence of interleukin-2 and interleukin-7. Responding CTL were amplified by restimulation rounds with HLA-A*0201-expressing JY lymphoblastoid cells pulsed with peptides and allogeneic PBMC asfeeder cells.  The assay was performed with repeated rounds of stimulation, with the efficiency of cytoloysis increasing with more stimulation.

Table 1, Figure 1, 2,4	in vivo assay	pathogen burden after challenge		http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0001475	Positive			9	9	100																		Source Organism	Organism	Influenza A virus H3N2								Influenza A virus H3N2	http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_41857	Influenza A virus	http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_11320	Virus titers in the lungs on day 5 after the challenge were determined from the numbers of plaques.  Virus titers of mice immunized with liposomal NP366-374 were significantly lower than controls.  Three intranasal immunizations was shown to confer significant protection, while subcutaneous immunization provided no effective immunityin the lung.  Also, this protective immunity was shown to last at least 8 weeks.  When tested, neither MHC class I- nor class II-deficient mice immunized intranasally with these materials were resistant to the infection, suggesting that both CD4+ and CD8+ cells may be involved in the clearance of the virus from mouse lungs.
